ial problems imported into the prison setting become part of the intricate web of prison culture. Their study reveals just how extensively women's prison experience reflects the control and domination they experienced in the outside world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aSex rolezUnited States. 0aWomen prisonerszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aBosworth, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEriksen, M. Elaine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerraro, Kathleen J, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGirshick, Lori B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeffernan, Esther, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Richard S, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLutze, Faith E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoe, Angela M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmid, Thomas J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSharp, Susan F, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThomas, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThomas, Jim, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aZaitzow, Barbara H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZaitzow, Barbara H., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertLynne Rienner Press Complete eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311078425140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978158826945440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781588269454423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781588269454